Well I have issues to reproduce it, because u need to configure nhibernate, then automapper and the DTOs and then if its not working, you just need to readjust everything and nhibernate is clever so you cant load/unload object, he will keep them in cache.

But hazzik explained it very well in its first post. Considering the same scheme where Animal is abstract.
Suppose automapper meets an AnimalProxy, he's looking, well is it linked to anything I know ? 
Who are you AnimalProxy ? Nhibernate answer, well I'm an Animal, but I dont know if im a Cat or a Dog, YET !
So Automapper saying yes but Animal is abstract, how am I supposed to create an instance of Animal ?
Well I would say that you could dynamically create this class

public AnimalDynamicMapping : Animal
{}

Then just make an instance of it and Map your animal with it. Its not perfect because :

Say we have:

public abstract Animal
{
   public bool IsAlive {get/set}
}
Turtle : Animal
{
    public Animal Friend {get/set}
}
Fish : Animal
{
   public Fish Friend {get/set}
}

Maybe in your DB you have the Friend of one Fish who is the same than the Friend of the Turtle.
In that case you will create two references to describe the same object. Boooooooh
But maybe you just want to know if the friend of the turtle is Alive.
In that case it will work. Now if you want to count the number of Dead friends, you could end up counting twice the same one > Here you just have to be aware of it depending on your design.

Its not perfect but it would be very great to have the option of doing it.
